WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.980
 - Hello and welcome to our lecture on simple django models.

00:00:03.980 --> 00:00:06.880
 Now, as you've seen in previous lectures,

00:00:06.880 --> 00:00:09.040
 we talked about SQL, structured query language,

00:00:09.040 --> 00:00:10.620
 and that's how we talk to databases,

00:00:10.620 --> 00:00:13.380
 and it's beautiful because it allows portability

00:00:13.380 --> 00:00:15.780
 up to a point across databases,

00:00:15.780 --> 00:00:19.480
 and we talked about all the create table stuff,

00:00:19.480 --> 00:00:22.780
 and so this is just a bit of review where, you know,

00:00:22.780 --> 00:00:25.240
 we can type these commands to SQLite.

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:28.880
 We run SQLite, we run a create table statement,

00:00:28.880 --> 00:00:31.600
 and, you know, we do it, and it's a dot tables that we go,

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:33.040
 we can ask kind of schema users,

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:36.180
 we did all this in a previous lecture,

00:00:36.180 --> 00:00:40.800
 and so that's basically how SQL works,

00:00:40.800 --> 00:00:43.940
 and here's a series of SQL commands from a previous lecture,

00:00:43.940 --> 00:00:47.300
 just kind of as review, it's pretty simple, crud.

00:00:47.300 --> 00:00:50.660
 Now, one of the problems is, as I mentioned,

00:00:50.660 --> 00:00:54.020
 is that different databases like PostgreSQL and MySQL

00:00:54.020 --> 00:00:55.540
 do all this stuff identical,

00:00:55.540 --> 00:00:57.500
 but then some more subtle things,

00:00:57.500 --> 00:01:00.720
 like how foreign keys work, which we'll learn in a bit,

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:03.660
 or how they do limits,

00:01:03.660 --> 00:01:07.100
 like pulling like 25, next 25, next 25,

00:01:07.100 --> 00:01:09.100
 that's a little bit different,

00:01:09.100 --> 00:01:11.300
 and so if you wanna build an application

00:01:11.300 --> 00:01:14.260
 that talks across more than one database,

00:01:14.260 --> 00:01:16.060
 you gotta think a little bit,

00:01:16.060 --> 00:01:18.020
 and one solution to this,

00:01:18.020 --> 00:01:22.180
 also to kind of limit the fancy SQL you have to learn,

00:01:22.180 --> 00:01:26.020
 I like to say that, you know,

00:01:26.020 --> 00:01:29.940
 you can learn the first 60% of SQL in about three hours,

00:01:29.940 --> 00:01:33.920
 and the last 40% is literally a lifetime,

00:01:33.920 --> 00:01:38.560
 I mean, and so it's, advanced SQL is difficult to do,

00:01:38.560 --> 00:01:42.540
 it's really hard to teach a class in advanced SQL,

00:01:42.540 --> 00:01:44.500
 I can teach you advanced features,

00:01:44.500 --> 00:01:46.360
 but then there are so many features

00:01:46.360 --> 00:01:48.140
 that you just can't learn in a class,

00:01:48.140 --> 00:01:49.820
 because which database you're using,

00:01:49.820 --> 00:01:51.620
 they're different for every database.

00:01:51.620 --> 00:01:54.360
 So one of the things that's happened

00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:56.260
 in the past decade or so,

00:01:56.260 --> 00:01:59.980
 is the emergence of what's called object relational mappers,

00:01:59.980 --> 00:02:03.420
 and that is to, you have the physical database layer,

00:02:03.420 --> 00:02:05.820
 and then you have SQL, which is an abstraction,

00:02:05.820 --> 00:02:07.980
 it's a imperfect abstraction,

00:02:07.980 --> 00:02:10.620
 and then Django builds another abstraction on top of that,

00:02:10.620 --> 00:02:12.020
 called object relational mappers,

00:02:12.020 --> 00:02:15.260
 so we just create a Python object,

00:02:15.260 --> 00:02:17.400
 and we ask that to be placed in the table,

00:02:17.400 --> 00:02:20.860
 now the object may have a name, an email address,

00:02:20.860 --> 00:02:23.720
 and you know, a birthday or something in it,

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:25.940
 it can have all kinds of data in that object,

00:02:25.940 --> 00:02:29.220
 and then that maps into a name and an email address,

00:02:29.220 --> 00:02:30.580
 and we have to tell it like,

00:02:30.580 --> 00:02:32.260
 do we want this to be indexed,

00:02:32.260 --> 00:02:33.360
 and all these other kinds of things,

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:35.220
 we communicate through the ORM,

00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:37.180
 so we leave the ORM alone.

00:02:37.180 --> 00:02:40.340
 Now in Django, as we get more advanced,

00:02:40.340 --> 00:02:42.260
 you can also sort of bypass the ORM,

00:02:42.260 --> 00:02:46.340
 because the way the objects are mapped into the tables,

00:02:46.340 --> 00:02:50.460
 is predictable, the names of the columns is predictable,

00:02:50.460 --> 00:02:53.620
 and so it's kind of like it's a shortcut

00:02:53.620 --> 00:02:56.940
 for, I like to think it's like the 80%

00:02:56.940 --> 00:02:59.300
 of the most common things you do with a database,

00:02:59.300 --> 00:03:01.180
 are easily done with an object relational model,

00:03:01.180 --> 00:03:02.340
 but object ORM,

00:03:02.340 --> 00:03:08.840
 but ultimately, once you get to the more advanced things,

00:03:08.840 --> 00:03:11.120
 you tend to not be able to do that with an ORM,

00:03:11.120 --> 00:03:14.140
 you get to the point where writing the SQL

00:03:14.140 --> 00:03:15.560
 is easier than using the ORM,

00:03:15.560 --> 00:03:18.040
 but for about 80%, writing ORM code

00:03:18.040 --> 00:03:21.520
 is way easier than writing the SQL.

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:25.560
 The other thing that ORM does, is it allows you to

00:03:25.560 --> 00:03:28.960
 have multiple databases, because the ORM code

00:03:28.960 --> 00:03:32.760
 inside of Django, knows the difference between

00:03:32.760 --> 00:03:35.700
 SQLite, PostgreSQL, and MySQL,

00:03:35.700 --> 00:03:38.940
 and so you could actually start an application

00:03:38.940 --> 00:03:40.980
 that uses SQLite during all your development,

00:03:40.980 --> 00:03:42.300
 and then when you're devoted to production,

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:43.460
 you just go like, you know what,

00:03:43.460 --> 00:03:46.180
 let's just use MySQL or PostgreSQL instead,

00:03:46.180 --> 00:03:48.440
 and that's quite cool.

00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:50.420
 I find them limiting, and so just,

00:03:50.420 --> 00:03:52.560
 I want you to know both how to use objects,

00:03:52.560 --> 00:03:55.860
 and how to use SQL, but understand that most of what

00:03:55.860 --> 00:03:58.360
 you're going to do is to use the object relational mapping,

00:03:58.360 --> 00:04:01.360
 and we get a lot of power with this.

00:04:01.360 --> 00:04:07.220
 So, if we look at sort of the way we communicate

00:04:07.220 --> 00:04:11.060
 to the database, or the way we define the database,

00:04:11.060 --> 00:04:15.220
 in SQL, we create a table, and that right there is portable,

00:04:15.220 --> 00:04:18.520
 but once you start doing things like adding

00:04:18.520 --> 00:04:20.160
 auto increment columns and things like that,

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:22.660
 it stops being portable.

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:25.180
 And so that's the way we do it, but in Django,

00:04:25.180 --> 00:04:28.620
 the way we do this is we have a file called models.py,

00:04:28.620 --> 00:04:32.100
 and it's in the application folder,

00:04:32.100 --> 00:04:34.700
 and then we are going to use object orientation,

00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:37.860
 so we're gonna, from Django.db, that's a package,

00:04:37.860 --> 00:04:42.820
 we're gonna import models, and models is now a class,

00:04:42.820 --> 00:04:46.380
 and we're gonna create a class called user,

00:04:46.380 --> 00:04:49.740
 this is going to be equivalent to the name of the table,

00:04:49.740 --> 00:04:53.900
 and the definition, we're gonna extend models.model,

00:04:53.900 --> 00:04:59.180
 and so there's a lot of it, this is called extending,

00:04:59.180 --> 00:05:02.980
 it's called inheritance, we're gonna get a lot of features

00:05:02.980 --> 00:05:05.480
 and functionality, excuse me,

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:10.820
 we're gonna get a lot of features and functionality

00:05:10.820 --> 00:05:14.260
 from this code, so there's probably 20,000 lines

00:05:14.260 --> 00:05:17.140
 of fancy code that we didn't write that we're using

00:05:17.140 --> 00:05:20.720
 by extending models.model, we're getting all that.

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:22.860
 And then within here, we create a couple of attributes

00:05:22.860 --> 00:05:25.280
 that basically says give me a character field,

00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:29.540
 models is a class, char field is a method within that class,

00:05:29.540 --> 00:05:32.940
 max length equals 128, and that gives us the name.

00:05:32.940 --> 00:05:35.900
 These two things are equivalent, and what happens is,

00:05:35.900 --> 00:05:37.900
 is when we build this, and we do what's called

00:05:37.900 --> 00:05:41.220
 run on migration, then Django will make this table for us,

00:05:41.220 --> 00:05:44.340
 but then we have this abstraction that we can use

00:05:44.340 --> 00:05:45.500
 to talk to it.

00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:49.540
 So this is called a migration, and so you have to be

00:05:49.540 --> 00:05:54.100
 in the projects folder, and so once you create a migration

00:05:54.100 --> 00:05:58.840
 inside of your Django application, then you go up

00:05:58.840 --> 00:06:02.140
 into the Django project, and you say python3 manage.py,

00:06:02.140 --> 00:06:05.940
 now manage.py is kind of like the thing

00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:08.980
 that starts everything, so make migrations

00:06:08.980 --> 00:06:12.460
 is actually creating files, 'cause the idea with migrations

00:06:12.460 --> 00:06:15.580
 is that you would debug your migrations,

00:06:15.580 --> 00:06:18.760
 like on your development environment, and then once you know,

00:06:18.760 --> 00:06:20.760
 you would move them to production.

00:06:20.760 --> 00:06:23.020
 So you'd make the migrations in development environment,

00:06:23.020 --> 00:06:24.940
 you'd get them right, and then you'd like check them

00:06:24.940 --> 00:06:27.680
 into GitHub perhaps, and then in production,

00:06:27.680 --> 00:06:30.120
 you would pull your migrations out of GitHub,

00:06:30.120 --> 00:06:32.920
 and then the migrate, so the make migrations,

00:06:32.920 --> 00:06:37.940
 the make migrations bit, that is creating a set

00:06:37.940 --> 00:06:40.940
 of migration scripts, and you can see that it's making

00:06:40.940 --> 00:06:42.960
 these files, and they're actual files, and you can go find

00:06:42.960 --> 00:06:46.900
 those files, like oh, one initial py, and then the migrate

00:06:46.900 --> 00:06:50.420
 is reading the migrations, and then actually changing

00:06:50.420 --> 00:06:53.860
 the database, so that's the one where you might be able

00:06:53.860 --> 00:06:56.860
 to make a migration, and it doesn't matter what database

00:06:56.860 --> 00:06:59.540
 you're gonna use, could be your development in SQLite,

00:06:59.540 --> 00:07:03.480
 and production in MySQL, you would do migrate

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:05.660
 in both of those, and in your development,

00:07:05.660 --> 00:07:07.940
 it would make an SQLite database, and in your production,

00:07:07.940 --> 00:07:10.460
 it would make a MySQL database, put the tables in,

00:07:10.460 --> 00:07:12.800
 and the SQL might even be quite subtle,

00:07:12.800 --> 00:07:15.100
 and it will be subtly different between them,

00:07:15.100 --> 00:07:17.680
 but you don't care, so migrate is the act

00:07:17.680 --> 00:07:19.820
 of creating the database.

00:07:19.820 --> 00:07:22.860
 Now in our development environments, we're gonna be creating

00:07:22.860 --> 00:07:27.860
 a file called db.sqlite3, and so if you get all messed up,

00:07:27.860 --> 00:07:30.020
 you don't have to remake your migrations,

00:07:30.020 --> 00:07:31.540
 they're just sitting there kind of as part

00:07:31.540 --> 00:07:33.940
 of your source code, and you can like get rid

00:07:33.940 --> 00:07:37.340
 of the db.sqlite3 file, and then run the migrations again,

00:07:37.340 --> 00:07:39.580
 if you get kinda messed up.

00:07:39.580 --> 00:07:43.180
 So the make migrations reads this, and creates

00:07:43.180 --> 00:07:45.140
 these other little files, you can take a look at them,

00:07:45.140 --> 00:07:47.380
 they're kind of like Django's internal files,

00:07:47.380 --> 00:07:49.620
 they're Python, it's just you're not gonna write them

00:07:49.620 --> 00:07:54.620
 by yourself, but then the migrate reads the 001 initial.py,

00:07:54.620 --> 00:07:57.580
 and then actually creates SQL commands,

00:07:57.580 --> 00:08:00.420
 and runs those SQL commands for us.

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:03.620
 And so if we jump, after we've done this,

00:08:03.620 --> 00:08:07.580
 we see this file db.sqlite3, and we can jump in,

00:08:07.580 --> 00:08:10.180
 and take a look, again you have to be in the right folder,

00:08:10.180 --> 00:08:13.600
 so you'd be in the Django_projects,

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:15.180
 and then the folder of the project,

00:08:15.180 --> 00:08:17.300
 but there'd be a file called db.sqlite3,

00:08:17.300 --> 00:08:22.180
 go into a Linux command line, type sqlite3, db.sqlite3,

00:08:22.180 --> 00:08:24.500
 and you will find a whole bunch of things.

00:08:24.500 --> 00:08:26.820
 And when you go into sqlite and you type .tables,

00:08:26.820 --> 00:08:29.960
 you will see that Django has a bunch of migrations

00:08:29.960 --> 00:08:33.280
 that are all there from the sessions,

00:08:33.280 --> 00:08:34.820
 and stuff we're gonna learn how to use later,

00:08:34.820 --> 00:08:36.680
 authorization, et cetera, et cetera,

00:08:36.680 --> 00:08:39.860
 but then the particular data model that you created,

00:08:39.860 --> 00:08:41.660
 which is a user data model,

00:08:41.660 --> 00:08:43.820
 there's a table in there for that.

00:08:43.820 --> 00:08:47.380
 And if we use the schema command of sqlite3,

00:08:47.380 --> 00:08:50.700
 and we say, hey, what is in that user_model_user table,

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:53.340
 and it's you see a create statement, right?

00:08:53.340 --> 00:08:55.500
 And so this is the actual create statement

00:08:55.500 --> 00:09:00.500
 that the Django sent to sqlite to create the table.

00:09:00.500 --> 00:09:02.740
 And I was talking about some of these things

00:09:02.740 --> 00:09:03.660
 are quite predictable.

00:09:03.660 --> 00:09:05.340
 The name of the column is quite predictable,

00:09:05.340 --> 00:09:06.940
 ID, name, email, et cetera.

00:09:06.940 --> 00:09:09.220
 It adds the ID field for you automatically.

00:09:09.220 --> 00:09:10.420
 And most of it's portable,

00:09:10.420 --> 00:09:12.020
 like this part here is quite portable,

00:09:12.020 --> 00:09:15.500
 but this ID statement here, primary key auto increment,

00:09:15.500 --> 00:09:18.380
 turns out that if you're in MySQL, or Oracle,

00:09:18.380 --> 00:09:21.620
 or PostgreSQL, or SQLite, that's a little different,

00:09:21.620 --> 00:09:24.200
 but literally the migrate takes care of all that,

00:09:24.200 --> 00:09:26.320
 because the migrate knows that thing,

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:27.900
 and as MySQL changes,

00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:30.260
 that particular syntax doesn't change very much,

00:09:30.260 --> 00:09:33.860
 but as MySQL changes, then the Django stuff changes,

00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:35.980
 and it all kind of works out.

00:09:35.980 --> 00:09:38.580
 And so you can sort of run these commands

00:09:38.580 --> 00:09:40.340
 and then sneak back into the database,

00:09:40.340 --> 00:09:41.500
 and you can see what they've done,

00:09:41.500 --> 00:09:44.380
 but it's all very predictable.

00:09:44.380 --> 00:09:50.140
 Do you wanna spill my coffee on my computer?

00:09:50.140 --> 00:09:55.000
 So you can also talk, you're talking at the low level

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:56.340
 when you run the SQLite command,

00:09:56.340 --> 00:09:57.820
 but you can also be in that folder,

00:09:57.820 --> 00:10:02.020
 same folder that has db.sqlite and manage.py,

00:10:02.020 --> 00:10:04.280
 and then you can start what's called the shell.

00:10:04.280 --> 00:10:06.160
 So this is different than the Linux shell,

00:10:06.160 --> 00:10:07.180
 and you see the prompt change

00:10:07.180 --> 00:10:10.260
 from dollar sign to three chevrons,

00:10:10.260 --> 00:10:13.980
 and it's not the same as the Python shell,

00:10:13.980 --> 00:10:16.480
 although it is the same as the Python shell,

00:10:16.480 --> 00:10:19.140
 with a whole bunch of Django libraries that are pre-mounted.

00:10:19.140 --> 00:10:23.060
 Okay, and so if you just say Python 3, you'll get this,

00:10:23.060 --> 00:10:26.580
 but this next command that is from user model,

00:10:26.580 --> 00:10:28.880
 models import user, that will fail

00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:31.460
 unless you let manage.py start your shell,

00:10:31.460 --> 00:10:34.340
 because again, it loads a bunch of objects

00:10:34.340 --> 00:10:36.500
 and classes into your space,

00:10:36.500 --> 00:10:39.040
 and then all of a sudden user model.models works,

00:10:39.040 --> 00:10:41.660
 users there, et cetera, okay?

00:10:41.660 --> 00:10:46.660
 So this is pulling from your models.py file that you built,

00:10:46.660 --> 00:10:50.860
 and so user model is the application name,

00:10:50.860 --> 00:10:53.160
 and models is the models.py file,

00:10:53.160 --> 00:10:56.380
 we import the user model, which is in this case a class,

00:10:56.380 --> 00:11:01.020
 user is a class, and we're going to do a constructor call,

00:11:01.020 --> 00:11:03.340
 and so we're going to say let's make a new user,

00:11:03.340 --> 00:11:07.160
 set the name to Kristen, and the email to that email,

00:11:07.160 --> 00:11:09.820
 and this actually has not done anything in the database,

00:11:09.820 --> 00:11:13.940
 this creates, in effect, just a Python variable,

00:11:13.940 --> 00:11:16.740
 and then to force it to read written to the database,

00:11:16.740 --> 00:11:19.580
 we call u.save, and so save is a method

00:11:19.580 --> 00:11:21.340
 on this new user object.

00:11:21.340 --> 00:11:25.220
 Capital user, capital user is a class,

00:11:25.220 --> 00:11:28.460
 we're using a constructor to construct from the class

00:11:28.460 --> 00:11:29.980
 an actual instance, an object,

00:11:29.980 --> 00:11:32.340
 and then we get that into u, the instance object,

00:11:32.340 --> 00:11:35.740
 and then that object sits in our memory until we say save,

00:11:35.740 --> 00:11:38.080
 and then it also pushes it back to the database.

00:11:38.080 --> 00:11:40.080
 Now one of the things that the save does,

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:44.500
 it assigns, in effect, a serial number, or a row ID,

00:11:44.500 --> 00:11:46.580
 if you look at these, they start pretty predictably

00:11:46.580 --> 00:11:48.300
 at one, two, three, four, five,

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:49.940
 but if you're getting a bunch of things coming in

00:11:49.940 --> 00:11:52.820
 from a bunch of places, then the database just assigns

00:11:52.820 --> 00:11:57.540
 each object, each row, and that's part of that whole

00:11:57.540 --> 00:12:00.060
 auto increment thing, come on, go back up,

00:12:00.060 --> 00:12:02.220
 this whole auto increment thing,

00:12:02.220 --> 00:12:05.380
 that says, hey database, I'm gonna put your records in,

00:12:05.380 --> 00:12:06.980
 I'm gonna give you the name and the email,

00:12:06.980 --> 00:12:09.940
 and you come up with a number, but then when you're done,

00:12:09.940 --> 00:12:12.420
 I want you to tell me what the number is,

00:12:12.420 --> 00:12:14.260
 and this is how you get that number,

00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:16.020
 by saying, oh, print u.id.

00:12:16.020 --> 00:12:18.740
 Now if you printed u.id before you did the save,

00:12:18.740 --> 00:12:21.620
 it wouldn't exist, and then print u.email,

00:12:21.620 --> 00:12:24.260
 you can see this email is just the data we put in,

00:12:24.260 --> 00:12:29.260
 but now this is not only in your u variable,

00:12:29.260 --> 00:12:31.980
 but it's also in the database as well, okay?

00:12:31.980 --> 00:12:38.420
 Now, we can dig a little bit into

00:12:38.420 --> 00:12:41.340
 how this object relational mapping is working,

00:12:41.340 --> 00:12:43.340
 and so if you're in the middle,

00:12:43.340 --> 00:12:45.420
 you're doing things like that last statement,

00:12:45.420 --> 00:12:49.300
 you can, from Django DB import connection,

00:12:49.300 --> 00:12:51.220
 and then ask connection.queries,

00:12:51.220 --> 00:12:52.860
 and then what it does is it just shows you

00:12:52.860 --> 00:12:55.660
 a little bit of debug data, and what it did,

00:12:55.660 --> 00:12:58.820
 how it started, the fact that it ran an insert statement,

00:12:58.820 --> 00:13:00.980
 and again, this looks kind of familiar,

00:13:00.980 --> 00:13:04.940
 it's making up SQL for you for that insert,

00:13:04.940 --> 00:13:07.720
 the save statement, right, that save statement there,

00:13:07.720 --> 00:13:10.100
 it's making that insert for you,

00:13:10.100 --> 00:13:13.580
 and then you can actually see what it's doing, right?

00:13:13.580 --> 00:13:17.060
 And so this save, you know, set up a thing and save it,

00:13:17.060 --> 00:13:18.900
 you don't need to know insert into or whatever,

00:13:18.900 --> 00:13:21.780
 'cause the object relational model does it for you, right?

00:13:21.780 --> 00:13:23.660
 And this is kind of what we did before,

00:13:23.660 --> 00:13:26.340
 insert into capital users by hand.

00:13:26.340 --> 00:13:30.180
 And so again, you know, you'll find this ORM

00:13:30.180 --> 00:13:31.860
 is gonna save you a whole bunch of time

00:13:31.860 --> 00:13:34.660
 for 80% of the things that you do with the database.

00:13:34.660 --> 00:13:38.440
 And so you can do basic CRUD operations

00:13:38.440 --> 00:13:40.760
 with this object relational mapper.

00:13:40.760 --> 00:13:45.980
 The save is the insert, you can select,

00:13:45.980 --> 00:13:49.460
 is basically user object values,

00:13:49.460 --> 00:13:53.220
 that's like select star, so give me all of the objects.

00:13:53.220 --> 00:13:56.660
 A where clause is user objects filter,

00:13:56.660 --> 00:13:58.140
 and there's your where clause.

00:13:58.140 --> 00:13:59.900
 This is a, email's a column name,

00:13:59.900 --> 00:14:03.100
 and csev@umich.edu is a value in that column.

00:14:03.100 --> 00:14:05.140
 Values is actually go get 'em,

00:14:05.140 --> 00:14:07.540
 so you can create kind of a query,

00:14:07.540 --> 00:14:09.440
 so if you don't put values on,

00:14:09.440 --> 00:14:12.300
 you get sort of a query that's not yet executed,

00:14:12.300 --> 00:14:14.860
 and then values says go do it, do it now.

00:14:20.260 --> 00:14:23.220
 So you can do a different, you can delete something,

00:14:23.220 --> 00:14:25.580
 where you say, and so this is a little different syntax,

00:14:25.580 --> 00:14:28.140
 this is kind of a selector that says

00:14:28.140 --> 00:14:29.840
 these are the variables to select,

00:14:29.840 --> 00:14:32.620
 and .delete says, I mean the rows to select,

00:14:32.620 --> 00:14:34.500
 and then delete those rows.

00:14:34.500 --> 00:14:36.100
 So value says retrieve the rows,

00:14:36.100 --> 00:14:38.140
 delete says get rid of the rows,

00:14:38.140 --> 00:14:40.460
 and then you can, again, the same kind of thing,

00:14:40.460 --> 00:14:41.700
 this is kind of like a where clause,

00:14:41.700 --> 00:14:45.740
 user objects filter email equals csev@umich.edu.update,

00:14:45.740 --> 00:14:48.460
 and then change this column in a way,

00:14:48.460 --> 00:14:51.500
 and you can go retrieve all the values,

00:14:51.500 --> 00:14:55.140
 and there are things that correspond to lots of the SQL,

00:14:55.140 --> 00:14:58.780
 like give me all these values, order by email,

00:14:58.780 --> 00:14:59.840
 et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

00:14:59.840 --> 00:15:04.460
 So it's kind of a one-to-one mapping,

00:15:04.460 --> 00:15:08.660
 and you will, again, you're gonna do a lot of programming

00:15:08.660 --> 00:15:12.020
 using this ORM in Django,

00:15:12.020 --> 00:15:14.500
 and every once in a while you'll sneak down to SQL,

00:15:14.500 --> 00:15:18.340
 and that's why I sort of teach you the SQL first,

00:15:18.340 --> 00:15:20.660
 and there's lots and lots of fields

00:15:20.660 --> 00:15:23.480
 that might not actually be represented

00:15:23.480 --> 00:15:26.820
 exactly the same way in the database.

00:15:26.820 --> 00:15:29.020
 So for example, an email field.

00:15:29.020 --> 00:15:31.560
 Databases commonly don't have email fields.

00:15:31.560 --> 00:15:33.240
 There might be some databases that have emails,

00:15:33.240 --> 00:15:34.660
 and others that don't,

00:15:34.660 --> 00:15:36.420
 but because the object-relational mapper

00:15:36.420 --> 00:15:38.780
 is a layer between you and the database,

00:15:38.780 --> 00:15:41.460
 and you say I'd like this to be an email field,

00:15:41.460 --> 00:15:43.260
 then it can add rules and stuff,

00:15:43.260 --> 00:15:46.060
 like validity checking, et cetera,

00:15:46.060 --> 00:15:48.660
 to say you know what, that doesn't look like an email address.

00:15:48.660 --> 00:15:50.220
 And so there's all of these things,

00:15:50.220 --> 00:15:52.820
 and these are very useful.

00:15:52.820 --> 00:15:55.260
 And later we'll talk about connecting tables,

00:15:55.260 --> 00:15:56.820
 and we'll use things like foreign keys,

00:15:56.820 --> 00:15:59.540
 and many-to-many fields, and one-to-one fields,

00:15:59.540 --> 00:16:02.440
 and those are more, those are less about the data,

00:16:02.440 --> 00:16:04.600
 and more about the connections between tables,

00:16:04.600 --> 00:16:07.420
 which we'll talk in coming up soon.

00:16:07.420 --> 00:16:11.520
 And so just to give you sort of a bit of a sense

00:16:11.520 --> 00:16:16.120
 of where you're at, this is our application, right,

00:16:16.120 --> 00:16:17.820
 and so we have a browser on the left-hand side

00:16:17.820 --> 00:16:20.740
 with a user doing some clicking.

00:16:20.740 --> 00:16:23.980
 By now you may have created a urls.py file,

00:16:23.980 --> 00:16:27.360
 and that takes the syntax of the get request,

00:16:27.360 --> 00:16:30.100
 slash this, slash that, slash whatever,

00:16:30.100 --> 00:16:31.780
 and routes it to a particular view

00:16:31.780 --> 00:16:34.100
 coming from the views.py file.

00:16:34.100 --> 00:16:36.700
 You may or may not have made one of those.

00:16:36.700 --> 00:16:40.220
 Templates and forms help produce output,

00:16:40.220 --> 00:16:42.500
 but the models are our interaction

00:16:42.500 --> 00:16:44.280
 between us and the database.

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:46.840
 And so the actual code we write in Django

00:16:46.840 --> 00:16:49.820
 can talk through the models to the database,

00:16:49.820 --> 00:16:51.060
 which you may not have done yet,

00:16:51.060 --> 00:16:53.900
 but this shell is talking through the Django models

00:16:53.900 --> 00:16:55.580
 to the database as well.

00:16:55.580 --> 00:16:58.200
 And if you're starting to use the admin user interface,

00:16:58.200 --> 00:17:00.900
 the admin user interface talks to the database

00:17:00.900 --> 00:17:03.940
 to the models, and it's informed by the kind of things

00:17:03.940 --> 00:17:06.060
 that you add to admin.py.

00:17:06.060 --> 00:17:08.340
 If you want to use the Django admin interface

00:17:08.340 --> 00:17:11.100
 and have your model shown a particular way,

00:17:11.100 --> 00:17:12.180
 it's got a bunch of defaults,

00:17:12.180 --> 00:17:14.220
 but often you want to override those defaults,

00:17:14.220 --> 00:17:15.780
 and so that's what you put in.

00:17:15.780 --> 00:17:19.420
 And the model.py file informs this connection

00:17:19.420 --> 00:17:20.460
 between the database,

00:17:20.460 --> 00:17:22.860
 and it also sort of informs the kind of code

00:17:22.860 --> 00:17:25.980
 you write here in a view code, in Python,

00:17:25.980 --> 00:17:27.620
 or in the Python shell.

00:17:27.620 --> 00:17:29.740
 That's kind of the Django shell,

00:17:29.740 --> 00:17:34.540
 which is a Python shell with all that stuff added to it.

00:17:34.540 --> 00:17:37.020
 Okay, so this model.py is critical

00:17:37.020 --> 00:17:40.680
 to defining our relationship between all of our Python code

00:17:40.680 --> 00:17:44.860
 and the admin user interface and the actual database.

00:17:44.860 --> 00:17:49.860
 And so you'll see a recorded demo

00:17:49.860 --> 00:17:51.780
 where I go through a bunch of those things,

00:17:51.780 --> 00:17:52.940
 which I kind of just showed you.

00:17:52.940 --> 00:17:55.340
 It's just actually doing it in a demo form,

00:17:55.340 --> 00:17:57.580
 but it's all mostly in this lecture.

00:17:57.580 --> 00:18:01.100
 And so the Django model is Django's version

00:18:01.100 --> 00:18:03.500
 of an object-relational mapper.

00:18:03.500 --> 00:18:06.580
 You can write Python code after a while,

00:18:06.580 --> 00:18:09.480
 especially if you have an IDE

00:18:09.480 --> 00:18:11.860
 that can show you what objects have and stuff.

00:18:11.860 --> 00:18:13.500
 You tender, it's a lot easier to write,

00:18:13.500 --> 00:18:15.940
 whereas SQL, you have to know it and write it.

00:18:15.940 --> 00:18:19.380
 You gain database portability.

00:18:19.380 --> 00:18:20.860
 You can create these migrations

00:18:20.860 --> 00:18:23.700
 to both build your initial schema in your database

00:18:23.700 --> 00:18:26.420
 and then evolve that schema as your application evolves.

00:18:26.420 --> 00:18:28.100
 That's one of the more valuable things.

00:18:28.100 --> 00:18:30.460
 If you're building straight up SQL,

00:18:30.460 --> 00:18:32.340
 going from version one of your database

00:18:32.340 --> 00:18:33.620
 to version two of your database,

00:18:33.620 --> 00:18:37.000
 it is kind of frustrating and difficult.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:40.280
 Sometime migrating and evolving a database

00:18:40.280 --> 00:18:41.420
 is harder than actually writing

00:18:41.420 --> 00:18:43.420
 the SQL code in the first place.

00:18:43.420 --> 00:18:44.980
 And Django gives you right out of the box

00:18:44.980 --> 00:18:47.120
 this really cool administrator interface.

00:18:47.120 --> 00:18:52.040
 The models.py and admin.py will inform that.

00:18:52.040 --> 00:18:53.460
 And later we're gonna have all this

00:18:53.460 --> 00:18:54.660
 automatic form generation.

00:18:54.660 --> 00:18:57.180
 And so what we're doing here is it seems like

00:18:57.180 --> 00:18:59.380
 we put like three lines of code into some file

00:18:59.380 --> 00:19:01.180
 and then a whole bunch of magic happens.

00:19:01.180 --> 00:19:03.140
 And that's really how Django works.

00:19:03.140 --> 00:19:05.580
 And the idea is that way you as the developer

00:19:05.580 --> 00:19:08.440
 can focus on the columns of your database

00:19:08.440 --> 00:19:10.060
 and the forms that you wanna put up

00:19:10.060 --> 00:19:13.820
 and spend less and less time sort of manually building

00:19:13.820 --> 00:19:18.380
 HTML that's very sort of brittle

00:19:18.380 --> 00:19:21.260
 and SQL that's less brittle but still brittle.

00:19:21.260 --> 00:19:22.460
 And so that's the idea.

00:19:22.460 --> 00:19:25.420
 And so it's a little hard when you're getting started

00:19:25.420 --> 00:19:28.900
 because the amount of code you write is so small

00:19:28.900 --> 00:19:32.380
 and what that accomplishes is so great.

00:19:32.380 --> 00:19:34.700
 But after a while when you get all these little tiny pieces

00:19:34.700 --> 00:19:37.380
 figured out then all of a sudden you're like okay

00:19:37.380 --> 00:19:39.480
 now I wanna solve that end user's problem

00:19:39.480 --> 00:19:41.420
 and you can spend all your time solving that problem

00:19:41.420 --> 00:19:43.020
 rather than just making databases

00:19:43.020 --> 00:19:44.260
 and those kinds of things.

00:19:44.260 --> 00:19:48.220
 So see you in the next lecture.

00:19:48.220 --> 00:19:49.060
 Cheers.

00:19:49.060 --> 00:19:51.640
 (upbeat music)

